ace-pre-wrap">In her discussion, Nora Ammann argues that humanity is navigating a "narrow path" to avoid two distinct AI-driven catastrophe clusters: Domination and Chaos.
Specific AI Catastrophes
Ammann categorizes potential failures into two main failure modes:
 * Domination: This cluster includes "classical" rogue superintelligence scenarios where a single misaligned system (or a small group of actors using AI) accumulates enough power to impose its will on the rest of the world. This could manifest as a single system out of human control or as AI-enabled coups where individuals seize total power.
 * Chaos (Excessive Competition): This scenario involves a multipolar world where no single actor dominates, but everyone is locked in an intense, adversarial "race to the bottom". In this state, actors are so incentivized to spend resources on survival, defense, and power that they ignore negative externalities (like pollution or technological risk), leading to an erosion of human values and flourishing.
Main Themes and Key Arguments
 * Slow Takeoff Multipolar World: Ammann posits that we are in a "slow takeoff" period, meaning progress occurs through several inflection points rather than one sudden explosion. She estimates a significant uplift in software engineering capabilities by the end of 2026 and autonomously capable R&amp;D systems by 2028–2030.
 * The Window of Intervention: She argues that the next two to four years are path-defining. During this window, humans must build the infrastructure and "good structures" necessary to steer AI progress before autonomous R&amp;D makes human intervention significantly harder.
 * Justified Confidence through High Assurance: A central theme is moving away from "blind trust" in AI. Ammann advocates for "high assurance AI-enabled R&amp;D," where AI systems are designed to provide formal, reviewable proofs that their outputs meet specific safety and security specifications.
 * Building Human-AI Coalitions: To navigate between domination and chaos, Ammann suggests building resilient coalitions. This involves creating "public goods" infrastructure that allows AI agents to coordinate, engage in positive-sum trades, and manage negative externalities collectively.
 * Defense-Favored Civilizations: She argues for a "defense-favored" sociotechnical stack. For instance, using AI to write formally verified code that is fundamentally free of exploitable bugs would give defenders a systematic advantage over attackers, thereby stabilizing society during the AI transition.
