ds dark markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="290">Below is a <strong data-start="11" data-end="39">concrete, worked example</strong>, written in the same formal–explanatory register, showing how <strong data-start="102" data-end="113">Polyxan</strong> exhibits <em data-start="123" data-end="159">bidirectional, inspectable linkage</em> in the same structural sense as <strong data-start="192" data-end="216">Lynx-style hypertext</strong> and the <strong data-start="225" data-end="241">Vim tutorial</strong>, but with proofs instead of pages or keystrokes.</p>
<hr data-start="292" data-end="295">
<h3 data-start="297" data-end="346">Example: Bidirectional Proof Links in Polyxan</h3>
<p data-start="348" data-end="615">Consider a coordination environment in which an autonomous agent proposes to deploy a software artifact into a shared infrastructure. In Polyxan, this proposal is not a raw action but a <em data-start="534" data-end="549">linked object</em> consisting of an action declaration and an attached proof object.</p>
<p data-start="617" data-end="645">Let the proposed action be</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>=</mo><mtext>Deploy</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator="true">,</mo><mi>E</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo separator="true">,</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a := \text{Deploy}(M, E),</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">:=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Deploy</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.10903em;">M</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">E</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mpunct">,</span></span></span></span></span>
<p data-start="678" data-end="755">where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.10903em;">M</span></span></span></span> is a model or program and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">E</span></span></span></span> is the execution environment.</p>
<p data-start="757" data-end="804">The proposal is accompanied by a proof object</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>=</mo><mtext>Proof</mtext><mo fence="false" stretchy="true" minsize="1.2em" maxsize="1.2em">(</mo><mtext>Safety</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo separator="true">,</mo><mtext>Consent</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>E</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo separator="true">,</mo><mtext>ResourceBound</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator="true">,</mo><mi>E</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo fence="false" stretchy="true" minsize="1.2em" maxsize="1.2em">)</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\pi := \text{Proof}\big(\text{Safety}(M), \text{Consent}(E), \text{ResourceBound}(M,E)\big).</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">π</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">:=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1.2em; vertical-align: -0.35em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Proof</span></span><span class="mord"><span class="delimsizing size1">(</span></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Safety</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.10903em;">M</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Consent</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">E</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">ResourceBound</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.10903em;">M</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">E</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mord"><span class="delimsizing size1">)</span></span><span class="mord">.</span></span></span></span></span>
<h4 data-start="905" data-end="939">Forward Link (Action → Proof)</h4>
<p data-start="941" data-end="1014">From the action <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span>, one can traverse <em data-start="983" data-end="992">forward</em> to its justification:</p>
<ul data-start="1016" data-end="1125">
<li data-start="1016" data-end="1047">
<p data-start="1018" data-end="1047">“Why is this action allowed?”</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1048" data-end="1086">
<p data-start="1050" data-end="1086">“Which constraints does it satisfy?”</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1087" data-end="1125">
<p data-start="1089" data-end="1125">“Which specifications were assumed?”</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1127" data-end="1153">Formally, this is the map:</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟶</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a \;\longrightarrow\; \pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.522em; vertical-align: -0.011em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">⟶</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">π</span></span></span></span></span>
<p data-start="1187" data-end="1462">This mirrors a <strong data-start="1202" data-end="1220">Lynx hyperlink</strong> from a page to its references, or a <strong data-start="1257" data-end="1285">Vim tutorial instruction</strong> that says “press <code data-start="1303" data-end="1306">j</code> to move down” and immediately points to the rule governing cursor motion. The action is never standalone; it is always <em data-start="1426" data-end="1461">embedded in a justification graph</em>.</p>
<p data-start="1464" data-end="1611">In Polyxan, an auditor, another agent, or an automated checker can follow this link and mechanically verify the proof without executing the action.</p>
<hr data-start="1613" data-end="1616">
<h4 data-start="1618" data-end="1653">Backward Link (Proof → Action)</h4>
<p data-start="1655" data-end="1697">Crucially, the linkage is <em data-start="1681" data-end="1696">bidirectional</em>.</p>
<p data-start="1699" data-end="1801">From the proof <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">π</span></span></span></span>, one can traverse <em data-start="1742" data-end="1752">backward</em> to enumerate exactly which actions depend on it:</p>
<ul data-start="1803" data-end="1945">
<li data-start="1803" data-end="1848">
<p data-start="1805" data-end="1848">“What actions are justified by this proof?”</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1849" data-end="1896">
<p data-start="1851" data-end="1896">“If this assumption is revoked, what breaks?”</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1897" data-end="1945">
<p data-start="1899" data-end="1945">“Which deployments rely on this safety claim?”</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1947" data-end="1956">Formally:</p>
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mi>π</mi><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟶</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo separator="true">,</mo><mo>…</mo><mtext> </mtext><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\pi \;\longrightarrow\; \{ a_1, a_2, \dots \}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.522em; vertical-align: -0.011em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">π</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">⟶</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mopen">{</span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.3011em;"><span style="top: -2.55em; margin-left: 0em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">1</span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.15em;"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.3011em;"><span style="top: -2.55em; margin-left: 0em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.15em;"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="minner">…</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mclose">}</span></span></span></span></span>
<p data-start="2010" data-end="2403">This is the key property shared with <strong data-start="2047" data-end="2082">bidirectional hypertext systems</strong> and <strong data-start="2087" data-end="2107">the Vim tutorial</strong>. In Vim, the tutorial is not just a static document; every instruction corresponds to an actual command whose effects can be inspected, reversed, and recomposed. You do not merely read that <code data-start="2298" data-end="2302">dd</code> deletes a line; you can navigate backward to understand which edits were produced by which commands.</p>
<p data-start="2405" data-end="2655">Similarly, Polyxan proofs are <em data-start="2435" data-end="2458">live semantic anchors</em>. Revoking or invalidating a proof automatically invalidates all actions that rely on it, just as removing a linked document in a hypertext system reveals broken links rather than silently failing.</p>
<hr data-start="2657" data-end="2660">
<h4 data-start="2662" data-end="2709">Contrast with Unidirectional Trust Systems</h4>
<p data-start="2711" data-end="2791">In most contemporary AI governance systems, the linkage is one-way and informal:</p>
<ul data-start="2793" data-end="2953">
<li data-start="2793" data-end="2815">
<p data-start="2795" data-end="2815">A model is deployed.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2816" data-end="2855">
<p data-start="2818" data-end="2855">A document claims it was “evaluated.”</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2856" data-end="2918">
<p data-start="2858" data-end="2918">The evaluation is not mechanically linked to the deployment.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2919" data-end="2953">
<p data-start="2921" data-end="2953">Revocation has no causal effect.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2955" data-end="3096">This is analogous to a <strong data-start="2978" data-end="2998">PDF on a website</strong> rather than a Lynx-style navigable document. The reference exists rhetorically, not structurally.</p>
<p data-start="3098" data-end="3209">Polyxan rejects this. Proofs are not comments; they are <em data-start="3154" data-end="3175">addressable objects</em> in the same namespace as actions.</p>
<hr data-start="3211" data-end="3214">
<h4 data-start="3216" data-end="3265">Vim Tutorial Analogy (Operational Semantics)</h4>
<p data-start="3267" data-end="3462">The Vim tutorial is effective because it teaches by <em data-start="3319" data-end="3338">reversible action</em>. Every instruction is immediately executable, observable, and undoable. Meaning is constructed through a trace of commands.</p>
<p data-start="3464" data-end="3525">Polyxan operates identically, but at the level of governance:</p>
<ul data-start="3527" data-end="3775">
<li data-start="3527" data-end="3551">
<p data-start="3529" data-end="3551">An action is proposed.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3552" data-end="3584">
<p data-start="3554" data-end="3584">Its justification is explicit.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3585" data-end="3622">
<p data-start="3587" data-end="3622">The justification can be inspected.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3623" data-end="3703">
<p data-start="3625" data-end="3703">The action can be rejected, accepted, or invalidated by modifying constraints.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3704" data-end="3775">
<p data-start="3706" data-end="3775">The system state is the fold over this history, not an opaque result.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3777" data-end="3883">This is precisely the event-sourced, proof-carrying analogue of learning Vim by doing rather than reading.</p>
<hr data-start="3885" data-end="3888">
<h4 data-start="3890" data-end="3942">Why This Matters for Alignment and Coordination</h4>
<p data-start="3944" data-end="3976">Because links are bidirectional:</p>
<ol data-start="3978" data-end="4554">
<li data-start="3978" data-end="4118">
<p data-start="3981" data-end="4118"><strong data-start="3981" data-end="4013">Accountability is structural</strong><br data-start="4013" data-end="4016">
One cannot ask “who approved this?” without immediately encountering the proof and its assumptions.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4120" data-end="4242">
<p data-start="4123" data-end="4242"><strong data-start="4123" data-end="4161">Revocation is causal, not symbolic</strong><br data-start="4161" data-end="4164">
Invalidating a constraint propagates mechanically to all dependent actions.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4244" data-end="4424">
<p data-start="4247" data-end="4424"><strong data-start="4247" data-end="4276">Coordination is navigable</strong><br data-start="4276" data-end="4279">
Agents can explore the space of allowed actions the way a Lynx user explores a document graph, rather than guessing based on policy summaries.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4426" data-end="4554">
<p data-start="4429" data-end="4554"><strong data-start="4429" data-end="4470">Acceleration does not break oversight</strong><br data-start="4470" data-end="4473">
Faster action generation does not erase the proof graph; it merely adds nodes.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr data-start="4556" data-end="4559">
<h4 data-start="4561" data-end="4581">Summary Insight</h4>
<p data-start="4583" data-end="4663">Polyxan behaves like <strong data-start="4604" data-end="4662">a bidirectional hypertext system for action legitimacy</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="4665" data-end="4811">Where Lynx links pages, Polyxan links actions to proofs.<br data-start="4721" data-end="4724">
Where Vim links commands to state transitions, Polyxan links commitments to invariants.</p>
<p data-start="4813" data-end="4908" data-is-last-node="" data-is-only-node="">This is not a metaphor layered on top of governance.<br data-start="4865" data-end="4868">
It <em data-start="4871" data-end="4875">is</em> the governance mechanism itself.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="z-0 flex min-h-[46px] justify-start"><div class="touch:-me-2 touch:-ms-3.5 -ms-2.5 -me-1 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-y-4 p-1 select-none touch:w-[calc(100%+--spacing(3.5))] -mt-1 w-[calc(100%+--spacing(2.5))] duration-[1.5s] focus-within:transition-none hover:transition-none touch:pointer-events-auto pointer-events-none [mask-image:linear-gradient(to_right,black_33%,transparent_66%)] [mask-size:300%_100%] [mask-position:100%_0%] motion-safe:transition-[mask-position] group-hover/turn-messages:pointer-events-auto group-hover/turn-messages:[mask-position:0_0] group-focus-within/turn-messages:pointer-events-auto group-focus-within/turn-messages:[mask-position:0_0] has-data-[state=open]:pointer-events-auto has-data-[state=open]:[mask-position:0_0]" style="mask-position: 0% 0%;"><button class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-bg-secondary rounded-lg" aria-label="Copy" aria-pressed="false" data-testid="copy-turn-action-button" data-state="closed"><span class="flex items-center justify-center touch:w-10 h-8 w-8"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="icon"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-k5zux585.svg#ce3544" fill="currentColor"></use></svg></span></button><button class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-bg-secondary rounded-lg" aria-label="Good response" aria-pressed="false" data-testid="good-response-turn-action-button" data-state="closed"><span class="flex items-center justify-center touch:w-10 h-8 w-8"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="icon"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-k5zux585.svg#51753c" fill="currentColor"></use></svg></span></button><button class="text-token-text-secondary hover:bg-token-bg-secondary rounded-lg" aria-label="Bad response" aria-pressed="false" data-testid="bad-response-turn-action-button" data-state