</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Appendix A: Formal Grammar of Event-Sourced and Proof-Carrying Systems}

This appendix presents a Backus–Naur Form (BNF) grammar defining the syntactic structure of event-sourced, proof-carrying coordination systems as described in the main text. The grammar specifies admissible constructions without prescribing semantics beyond well-formedness.

Let terminal symbols be written in typewriter font and non-terminals in angle brackets.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Lexical Primitives}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{verbatim}<span class="hljs-string">
&lt;Identifier&gt; ::= letter (letter | digit | "_")*
&lt;Scalar&gt;     ::= integer | float
&lt;Bool&gt;       ::= "true" | "false"
</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{verbatim}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Event Structure}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{verbatim}<span class="hljs-string">
&lt;Event&gt; ::= "event" &lt;Identifier&gt; ":" &lt;EventType&gt; &lt;EventPayload&gt;

&lt;EventType&gt; ::= "consent"
              | "action"
              | "transformation"
              | "proof"
              | "revocation"

&lt;EventPayload&gt; ::= "{" &lt;DeclarationList&gt; "}"

&lt;DeclarationList&gt; ::= &lt;Declaration&gt;
                    | &lt;Declaration&gt; "," &lt;DeclarationList&gt;

&lt;Declaration&gt; ::= &lt;Identifier&gt; "=" &lt;Value&gt;

&lt;Value&gt; ::= &lt;Scalar&gt;
          | &lt;Bool&gt;
          | &lt;Identifier&gt;
          | &lt;Set&gt;
          | &lt;Vector&gt;
</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{verbatim}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Consent and Constraint Declarations}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{verbatim}<span class="hljs-string">
&lt;ConsentSpec&gt; ::= "forbid" &lt;SemanticRegion&gt;
               | "allow" &lt;SemanticRegion&gt;

&lt;SemanticRegion&gt; ::= &lt;Identifier&gt;
                   | &lt;Identifier&gt; "::" &lt;SemanticRegion&gt;
</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{verbatim}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Action and Proof Coupling}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{verbatim}<span class="hljs-string">
&lt;Action&gt; ::= "action" &lt;Identifier&gt; "(" &lt;ArgumentList&gt; ")"

&lt;ArgumentList&gt; ::= &lt;Argument&gt;
                 | &lt;Argument&gt; "," &lt;ArgumentList&gt;

&lt;Argument&gt; ::= &lt;Identifier&gt; ":" &lt;Type&gt;

&lt;Proof&gt; ::= "proof" &lt;Identifier&gt; ":" &lt;Specification&gt;

&lt;Specification&gt; ::= &lt;Predicate&gt;
                  | &lt;Predicate&gt; "AND" &lt;Specification&gt;

&lt;Predicate&gt; ::= &lt;Identifier&gt; "(" &lt;ArgumentList&gt; ")"
</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{verbatim}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Admissibility Judgment}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{verbatim}<span class="hljs-string">
&lt;Admissible&gt; ::= &lt;Action&gt; "⊢" &lt;Proof&gt;
</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{verbatim}

An action is syntactically admissible if and only if it appears in a well-formed admissibility judgment. Semantic admissibility is defined by categorical and sheaf-theoretic constructions given below.

---

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Appendix B: Categorical Formulation of Events, Proofs, and Admissibility}

This appendix formalizes the system using category theory. The purpose is not abstraction for its own sake, but to make explicit the compositional and functorial properties that guarantee scalability under acceleration.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Event Category}

Let </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{E} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> be a small category whose objects are events and whose morphisms represent causal precedence. The category is thin, i.e., for any two objects </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> e</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>1, e</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>2 </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span>, there exists at most one morphism </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> e</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>1 </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\to</span></span><span> e</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>2 </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span>, encoding a partial order.

Irreversibility is enforced by requiring </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{E} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> to be acyclic. Thus </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{E} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> is a posetal category.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Action and Proof Categories}

Let </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{A} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> be a category of action proposals, and let </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{P} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> be a category of proof objects. Objects in </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{P} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> are proofs; morphisms are proof refinements or extensions.

There exists a functor
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
F : </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{A} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\to</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{P}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
assigning to each action the specification it must satisfy.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Admissibility as a Pullback}

Let </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{S} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> be a category of specifications. There exist functors
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
G : </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{P} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\to</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{S}, </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\quad</span></span><span> H : </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{A} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\to</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{S}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
where </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> G </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> maps proofs to the specifications they discharge, and </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> H </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> maps actions to the specifications they require.

Admissible actions are defined by the pullback category
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{A}</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{adm}} = </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{A} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\times</span></span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{S}} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{P}.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>

This construction guarantees that admissibility is preserved under composition: composing two admissible actions corresponds to composing their proofs, provided the resulting specification remains satisfied.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Dominance of Proof-Carrying Systems}

Let </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{B} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subset</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{A} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> denote behavior-aligned actions. There exists a faithful embedding
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{B} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\hookrightarrow</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{A}</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{adm}},
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
but no functor in the reverse direction preserving safety invariants. This establishes the strict expressive dominance of proof-carrying governance.

---

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Appendix C: Sheaf-Theoretic Interpretation of Consent and Coordination}

This appendix interprets the system using sheaf theory, clarifying how local constraints compose into global coherence.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Semantic Base Space}

Let </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> X </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> be a topological space whose points correspond to semantic contexts and whose open sets represent admissible regions of interaction. The topology encodes refinement of context: smaller opens correspond to more specific scopes.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Sheaf of Actions}

Define a presheaf </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{F} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> on </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> X </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> such that for each open set </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> U </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subseteq</span></span><span> X </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span>,
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{F}(U)
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
is the set of actions admissible within semantic context </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> U </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span>.

Restriction maps correspond to narrowing scope. An action admissible in </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> U </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> may or may not restrict to </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> V </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subset</span></span><span> U </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span>, depending on consent constraints.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Consent as Sheaf Restriction}

A consent declaration corresponds to removing sections over forbidden opens. Formally, consent defines a subsheaf
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{F}</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{consent}} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subseteq</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{F}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
such that sections violating consent do not admit compatible restrictions.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Externalities as Gluing Obstructions}

Externalities arise when local admissibility fails to glue into a global section. Let </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\{</span></span><span>U</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>i</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\}</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> be an open cover of </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> X </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span>. A family of local actions </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\(</span></span><span> a</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>i </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\in</span></span><span> </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{F}(U</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>i) </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\)</span></span><span> is globally admissible if and only if it satisfies the sheaf gluing condition.

Negative externalities correspond precisely to failures of the cocycle condition: locally admissible actions that cannot be made consistent globally.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{PlenumHub as a Global Section Space}

PlenumHub enforces sheaf conditions by requiring that all actions extend to global sections. Actions that cannot be glued due to externality constraints are rejected before execution.

This guarantees that coordination is not emergent but enforced by the topology of admissibility itself.

---

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Appendix D: Structural Elimination of Pathological Attractors}

In sheaf-theoretic terms, domination corresponds to singular global sections that ignore local restrictions, while chaos corresponds to incompatible local sections that fail to glue.

By enforcing sheaf conditions mechanically, the system admits neither singularities nor incoherent covers. The space of admissible trajectories is therefore compact and stable under refinement.

This completes the formal foundation underlying the main text.
