\section{Appendix A: Formal Grammar of Event-Sourced and Proof-Carrying Systems}

This appendix presents a Backus–Naur Form (BNF) grammar defining the syntactic structure of event-sourced, proof-carrying coordination systems as described in the main text. The grammar specifies admissible constructions without prescribing semantics beyond well-formedness.

Let terminal symbols be written in typewriter font and non-terminals in angle brackets.

\subsection{Lexical Primitives}

\begin{verbatim}
&lt;Identifier&gt; ::= letter (letter | digit | "_")*
&lt;Scalar&gt;     ::= integer | float
&lt;Bool&gt;       ::= "true" | "false"
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Event Structure}

\begin{verbatim}
&lt;Event&gt; ::= "event" &lt;Identifier&gt; ":" &lt;EventType&gt; &lt;EventPayload&gt;

&lt;EventType&gt; ::= "consent"
              | "action"
              | "transformation"
              | "proof"
              | "revocation"

&lt;EventPayload&gt; ::= "{" &lt;DeclarationList&gt; "}"

&lt;DeclarationList&gt; ::= &lt;Declaration&gt;
                    | &lt;Declaration&gt; "," &lt;DeclarationList&gt;

&lt;Declaration&gt; ::= &lt;Identifier&gt; "=" &lt;Value&gt;

&lt;Value&gt; ::= &lt;Scalar&gt;
          | &lt;Bool&gt;
          | &lt;Identifier&gt;
          | &lt;Set&gt;
          | &lt;Vector&gt;
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Consent and Constraint Declarations}

\begin{verbatim}
&lt;ConsentSpec&gt; ::= "forbid" &lt;SemanticRegion&gt;
               | "allow" &lt;SemanticRegion&gt;

&lt;SemanticRegion&gt; ::= &lt;Identifier&gt;
                   | &lt;Identifier&gt; "::" &lt;SemanticRegion&gt;
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Action and Proof Coupling}

\begin{verbatim}
&lt;Action&gt; ::= "action" &lt;Identifier&gt; "(" &lt;ArgumentList&gt; ")"

&lt;ArgumentList&gt; ::= &lt;Argument&gt;
                 | &lt;Argument&gt; "," &lt;ArgumentList&gt;

&lt;Argument&gt; ::= &lt;Identifier&gt; ":" &lt;Type&gt;

&lt;Proof&gt; ::= "proof" &lt;Identifier&gt; ":" &lt;Specification&gt;

&lt;Specification&gt; ::= &lt;Predicate&gt;
                  | &lt;Predicate&gt; "AND" &lt;Specification&gt;

&lt;Predicate&gt; ::= &lt;Identifier&gt; "(" &lt;ArgumentList&gt; ")"
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Admissibility Judgment}

\begin{verbatim}
&lt;Admissible&gt; ::= &lt;Action&gt; "⊢" &lt;Proof&gt;
\end{verbatim}

An action is syntactically admissible if and only if it appears in a well-formed admissibility judgment. Semantic admissibility is defined by categorical and sheaf-theoretic constructions given below.

---

\section{Appendix B: Categorical Formulation of Events, Proofs, and Admissibility}

This appendix formalizes the system using category theory. The purpose is not abstraction for its own sake, but to make explicit the compositional and functorial properties that guarantee scalability under acceleration.

\subsection{Event Category}

Let \( \mathcal{E} \) be a small category whose objects are events and whose morphisms represent causal precedence. The category is thin, i.e., for any two objects \( e_1, e_2 \), there exists at most one morphism \( e_1 \to e_2 \), encoding a partial order.

Irreversibility is enforced by requiring \( \mathcal{E} \) to be acyclic. Thus \( \mathcal{E} \) is a posetal category.

\subsection{Action and Proof Categories}

Let \( \mathcal{A} \) be a category of action proposals, and let \( \mathcal{P} \) be a category of proof objects. Objects in \( \mathcal{P} \) are proofs; morphisms are proof refinements or extensions.

There exists a functor
\[
F : \mathcal{A} \to \mathcal{P}
\]
assigning to each action the specification it must satisfy.

\subsection{Admissibility as a Pullback}

Let \( \mathcal{S} \) be a category of specifications. There exist functors
\[
G : \mathcal{P} \to \mathcal{S}, \quad H : \mathcal{A} \to \mathcal{S}
\]
where \( G \) maps proofs to the specifications they discharge, and \( H \) maps actions to the specifications they require.

Admissible actions are defined by the pullback category
\[
\mathcal{A}_{\text{adm}} = \mathcal{A} \times_{\mathcal{S}} \mathcal{P}.
\]

This construction guarantees that admissibility is preserved under composition: composing two admissible actions corresponds to composing their proofs, provided the resulting specification remains satisfied.

\subsection{Dominance of Proof-Carrying Systems}

Let \( \mathcal{B} \subset \mathcal{A} \) denote behavior-aligned actions. There exists a faithful embedding
\[
\mathcal{B} \hookrightarrow \mathcal{A}_{\text{adm}},
\]
but no functor in the reverse direction preserving safety invariants. This establishes the strict expressive dominance of proof-carrying governance.

---

\section{Appendix C: Sheaf-Theoretic Interpretation of Consent and Coordination}

This appendix interprets the system using sheaf theory, clarifying how local constraints compose into global coherence.

\subsection{Semantic Base Space}

Let \( X \) be a topological space whose points correspond to semantic contexts and whose open sets represent admissible regions of interaction. The topology encodes refinement of context: smaller opens correspond to more specific scopes.

\subsection{Sheaf of Actions}

Define a presheaf \( \mathcal{F} \) on \( X \) such that for each open set \( U \subseteq X \),
\[
\mathcal{F}(U)
\]
is the set of actions admissible within semantic context \( U \).

Restriction maps correspond to narrowing scope. An action admissible in \( U \) may or may not restrict to \( V \subset U \), depending on consent constraints.

\subsection{Consent as Sheaf Restriction}

A consent declaration corresponds to removing sections over forbidden opens. Formally, consent defines a subsheaf
\[
\mathcal{F}_{\text{consent}} \subseteq \mathcal{F}
\]
such that sections violating consent do not admit compatible restrictions.

\subsection{Externalities as Gluing Obstructions}

Externalities arise when local admissibility fails to glue into a global section. Let \( \{U_i\} \) be an open cover of \( X \). A family of local actions \( a_i \in \mathcal{F}(U_i) \) is globally admissible if and only if it satisfies the sheaf gluing condition.

Negative externalities correspond precisely to failures of the cocycle condition: locally admissible actions that cannot be made consistent globally.

\subsection{PlenumHub as a Global Section Space}

PlenumHub enforces sheaf conditions by requiring that all actions extend to global sections. Actions that cannot be glued due to externality constraints are rejected before execution.

This guarantees that coordination is not emergent but enforced by the topology of admissibility itself.

---

\section{Appendix D: Structural Elimination of Pathological Attractors}

In sheaf-theoretic terms, domination corresponds to singular global sections that ignore local restrictions, while chaos corresponds to incompatible local sections that fail to glue.

By enforcing sheaf conditions mechanically, the system admits neither singularities nor incoherent covers. The space of admissible trajectories is therefore compact and stable under refinement.

This completes the formal foundation underlying the main text.
